'''''Trypanosoma''''' is a notable genus of [[trypanosome]]s, a [[monophyletic]]<ref name="Hamilton04">{{cite journal
 | author = Hamilton, PB 
 | year = 2004
 | title = Trypanosomes are monophyletic: evidence from genes for glyceraldehyde phosphate dehydrogenase and small subunit ribosomal RNA.
 | journal = Int J Parasitol 
 | volume = 34
 | issue = 12
 | pages = 1393&ndash;1404
 | id = PMID 15542100
 }}</ref> group of unicellular [[parasite|parasitic]] protozoa.  The name is derived from the [[Greek language|Greek]] ''trypa&ocirc;'' (boring) and ''soma'' (body) because of the way the organisms move.  Different species infect a variety of different vertebrates, including humans, causing the [[trypanosomiasis]] diseases, e.g. [[sleeping sickness]].  Most species are transmitted by invertebrates such as biting [[insect]]s and [[leech]]es.  

Trypanosoma undergo a complex lifecycle which may include several different morphological forms especially in the species which are transmitted by invertebrates. They may go through a variety of different forms in the invertebrate host, but in the vertebrate host the cells take a characteristic form called a trypomastigote, where the flagellum runs from the posterior to the anterior of the cell and is connected by an undulating membrane.

Species of ''Trypanosoma'' include the following:
* ''[[Trypanosoma avium|T. avium]]'', which causes trypanosomiasis in birds
* ''[[Trypanosoma boissoni|T. boissoni]]'', in [[elasmobranch]]
* ''[[Trypanosoma brucei|T. brucei]]'', which causes [[sleeping sickness]] in humans and [[nagana]] in cattle
* ''[[Trypanosoma carassii|T. carassii]]'', in freshwater [[teleost]]s
* ''[[Trypanosoma cruzi|T. cruzi]]'', which causes [[Chagas disease]] in humans
* ''[[Trypanosoma congolese|T. congolense]]'', which causes [[nagana]] in cattle, horses, and camels
* ''[[Trypanosoma equinum]]'' Voges 1901, Horses infected by [[Tabanidae]], [[South America]]
* ''[[Trypanosoma equiperdum|T. equiperdum]]'', which causes [[dourine]] or [[Covering sickness]] in [[horse]]s and other [[Equidae]]
* ''[[Trypanosoma evansi|T. evansi]]'', which causes one form of the disease [[surra]] in certain animals (single case report of human infection in [[2005]] in India<ref>{{cite journal | 
 journal=Wkly Epidemiol Rec | year=2005 | volume=80 | issue=7 | pages=62&ndash;3 | title=A new form of human trypanosomiasis in India. Description of the first human case in the world caused by ''Trypanosoma evansi'' | author=World Health Organization. | id=PMID 15771199 |
